ce:section.ce:para:
The use of solar energy to drive catalytic reactions for H2O2 and H2 production, as well as for selective organic synthesis, is recognized as a sustainable strategy [
                        1,2
                     ]. Because reactions involving both electron and holes, that is, the oxygen reduction reaction (ORR) and water oxidation reaction (WOR), can simultaneously generate H2O2, the solar-to-H2O2 efficiency calculated using the photon flux is theoretically enhanced twofold, as compared to H2 production [
                        3,4
                     ]. As a carbon-neutral alternative, the photocatalytic synthesis of H2O2 using earth-abundant O2 and water is promising for replacing the industrial anthraquinone method, which is energy-intensive and environmentally unfriendly [
                        5–7
                     ]. The current critical research is focused on the search for efficient and environmentally friendly photocatalysts with high efficiency, good selectivity, and stability. Various metal-free polymeric and inorganic semiconductors have been developed for photocatalytic H2O2 production; however, their expected performance and solar-to-chemical conversion (SCC) efficiency still lag. This approach faces two major challenges. First, although many efforts have been made to improve the charge separation and utilization efficiency, including the loading of nanostructures and functional groups, rational design of defects, and heterogeneous element doping, the resulting charge separation and utilization efficiency are still very low [
                        8–10
                     ]. Second, most of these semiconductors have potential stability and durability issues owing to the associated reactive oxygen species, such as •OH and O2
                     •–, which damage catalyst structures [
                        11–13
                     ].

Covalent organic frameworks (COFs) are a new class of materials that are composed of covalently bonded light elements such as C, H, O, N, and S [
                        14–16
                     ]. Apart from their “earth-abundant” nature, their high structural stability and functional diversity, particularly their unique π-conjugated sp
                     2 C structures, allow for the integration of light harvesting and charge separation and transport into one material to be rationally designed, promoting photocatalytic reactions. This material has been used in a variety of photoresponsive reactions such as water splitting, CO2 reduction, organic synthesis, and pollutant degradation [
                        17–21
                     ]. Covalent triazine frameworks (CTFs), which contain robust aromatic triazine linkages, are a subclass of COFs. CTFs, as compared with COFs, contain stronger bonds and are rich in N. However, because of the poor reversibility of their conjugated bonds, the trimerization of cyano groups usually results in a disordered structure and irregular porosity [
                        22
                     ]. This phenomenon can drastically influence charge separation and transfer, a process whereby photoexcited electrons and holes are transported to the reaction interface, which mostly determine the photocatalytic activity [
                        23
                     ]. The combination of the prompt recombination of singlet Frenkel excitons with intrinsically strong Coulomb interactions in organic semiconductors has limited the application of CTFs as photocatalysts [
                        22,24
                     ]. The current strategies to facilitate the carrier separation efficiency of CTFs focus on developing highly crystalline structures and/or incorporating electron-donating and electron-accepting units with different ionization potentials and electron affinities into the CTF skeleton [
                        25–28
                     ]. For example, the incorporation of acetylene or diacetylene moieties into CTFs can enhance the H2O2 production rate by more than two-fold [
                        21
                     ]. Moreover, the partial fluorination of imine-linked CTFs results in a H2O2 yield rate of up to 1739 μmol h–1 g–1 and an apparent quantum efficiency of < 3% at 500 nm [
                        29
                     ]. However, the H2O2 production rates of the reported CTFs are lower than expected.

Carbon dots (CDs) are the missing link between the molecular and nanoscale worlds and can reform the microstructure and physical properties of various materials [
                        30–32
                     ]. CDs possess many advantages, including low cost, high stability, environmental friendliness, and tunable optical properties, and can also act as charge donors/acceptors and reservoirs, promoting charge transfer and suppressing the recombination of photocarriers [
                        33–35
                     ]. Considering this, numerous studies have demonstrated the implementation of CD-related hybrids and nanocomposites for artificial photosynthesis and solar energy conversion [
                        36–39
                     ]. Coal-based CDs fabricated by the oxidation etching of coal and coal pitch powder consist of crystalline C cores surrounded by surface terminal functional groups such as carbonyl groups, carboxylic acids, and alcohols [
                        40,41
                     ]. Such surface terminal groups regulate the reactivity, recognition, and binding interactions of CDs with the surrounding environment. The authors recently reported a solution-based approach to combine coal-based CDs with CTFs via the cyclotrimerization of 1,4-dicyanobenzene (DCB) at the interface between dichloromethane and trifluoromethanesulfonic acid [
                        42
                     ]. Although CDs can extract photoinduced holes from CTFs for the WOR, the charge separation and transfer efficiency remains very low because of the poor crystallinity of the CTFs, resulting in a SCC efficiency of only 0.16%.

CDs were prepared by the oxidation etching of coal pitch powder using a previously reported method [
                              40
                           ]. The CDs were further modified with ammonia to obtain NCDs, as previously reported [
                              43
                           ]. CDs (20 mg) were ultrasonically dispersed in 30 mL NH3·H2O, and the resultant suspension was transferred into a hydrothermal reactor for heating at 200 °C. After reacting for 3 h, the obtained product was dried in a vacuum oven at 60 °C to obtain NCDs.

Fig. 1(b) shows the photosynthetic H2O2 performance of CDs@CTFs, which exhibits a considerably higher H2O2 yield (1848 μmol h–1 g–1) than that of pure CTFs under one sun. The CDs@CTFs enabled a higher H2O2 production rate with an increasing solar intensity and reaction solution (Fig. S1). Since H+ ions are involved in the ORR through the reaction O2 + 2H+ + 2e– → H2O2, CDs@CTFs expectedly exhibited higher activity in acidic conditions (Fig. S2). Unlike the pure CTFs, CDs@CTFs efficiently generated H2O2 when the reaction solution was N2-purged and a NaIO3 sacrificial agent was added (Fig. 1(b)). Moreover, cyclic voltammetry (CV) measurements were performed in a 0.1 mol L–1 Na2SO4 solution to identify the active sites for donating and accepting electrons. The CV curve of the CDs@CTFs (Fig. S3) exhibited a new oxidation peak associated with adsorbed H2O and/or –OH [
   44
], suggesting the formation of oxidation sites in the CDs@CTFs. Notably, a reduction peak assigned to the adsorption/desorption of O2 was observed in the pure CTF CV curve, which positively shifted, as compared with that of CDs@CTFs, indicating that the CTFs were more electron-deficient than the CDs@CTFs [
   45
]. Therefore, CDs on CTFs play a vital role in spatial charge separation and water activation.

To further confirm the role of CDs in hole extraction, metal ions were employed to modulate the energy states at the CD surface, which could serve as the driving force for carrier separation and migration [
                           46,47
                        ]. Negatively charged CDs were first allowed to interact with metal ions in an aqueous solution (see below for details). After removing the solvents, the obtained solid powders were used to prepare CDs@CTFs using the synthetic method mentioned above (Scheme S1). Fig. 1(c) shows that the H2O2 yield rate can be increased from 1848 to 2464 μmol h–1 g–1 by adding a small amount (0.1 μmol) of CsCl to the CDs@CTFs. Additionally, the intensity of the oxidation peak in the CV curve of the CsCl-containing CDs@CTFs was higher than that of the CsCl-free CDs@CTFs (Fig. S7). This phenomenon indicates that the chemical adsorption of H2O and –OH on the CDs was strengthened by the introduction of CsCl. However, adding the same amount of CsCl to the obtained CTFs resulted in a reduced H2O2 photosynthetic rate (Fig. 1(c)), indicating that CDs are a key factor influencing photocatalytic H2O2 generation. It should be mentioned that the CDs enabled negligible H2O2 formation under illumination (Fig. 1(c)).

The wavelength-dependent AQYs corresponded with the absorption spectrum of CDs@CTFs containing CsCl (Fig. 2(a)
                        ), revealing that H2O2 was produced following band gap excitation [
                           50
                        ]. The AQY at 500 nm was determined to be 13%, which to the best of our knowledge, is the best recorded value for particulate photocatalysts (Table S1). Furthermore, the SCC efficiency at room temperature reached 0.90%, surpassing those of other previously reported photocatalysts (Fig. 2(b), Table S1). For comparison, the SCC efficiency and AQYs of the pure CTFs and CDs@CTFs were measured under the same conditions (Fig. S8). The pure CTFs and CDs@CTFs exhibited SCC values of 0.34% and 0.76%, respectively. Fig. 2(c) shows the long-term stability and reproducibility of CDs@CTFs for H2O2 production under simulated sunlight irradiation. The CsCl-containing CDs@CTFs exhibited similar activities after recycling. No changes in the phase structure were detected after repeated use (Fig. S9). Their photocatalytic activity after 100 d of laboratory storage was the same as that of the fresh sample. Additionally, the photocatalytic experiment was conducted from 08:00 to 18:00 under natural sunlight without the need for a cooling system. Fig. 2(d) shows the sunlight flux, air temperature, and H2O2 yield over time. The H2O2 yield under such conditions linearly increased with time and its cumulative production reached approximately 12000 μmol for every gram of catalyst. The H2O2 production of the proposed photocatalyst was tested on another day to confirm this result (Fig. S10); the proposed photocatalyst exhibited a consistent tendency.

The FTIR spectra (Fig. 3(a)
                        ) show that new characteristic peaks emerged at 1352 and 1519 cm–1 while the stretching peak at 2230 cm–1, which was ascribed to the C≡N groups of the monomers, reduced significantly, indicating that the simple calcination process at 250 °C led to the formation of triazine rings after trimerization [
                           51,52
                        ]. The powder XRD patterns exhibit intense peaks at 7.13, 12.51, 14.43, and 26.2° (Fig. 3(b)), which were assigned to the (100), (110), and (200) reflections and the stacked layer (002), respectively [
                           53
                        ]. These results verify the formation of highly crystalline CTFs. More interestingly, the evolution of the XRD patterns with the CD content indicated that an appropriate amount of CDs can improve the crystallinity of the CTFs, achieving optimal photocatalytic activity (Fig. S11). An appropriate CD content allows for the preferential growth of CTFs on the CD surfaces, benefiting the crystallization of the CTFs.

TEM was employed to confirm this phenomenon. The HRTEM images of the CDs@CTFs in Fig. 3(c) show that the CTF layers are stacked along the (100) planes of the CDs. Two distinct lattice fringes with spacings of 0.34 and 0.21 nm, corresponding to the stacked layer (002) planes of the CTFs and (100) facets of the graphitic C, respectively, were observed. The elemental composition and chemical bonds were further characterized using XPS, which indicated that CDs@CTFs contained carboxyl groups (Fig. 3(d)) owing to the introduction of CDs [
                           54,55
                        ]. CDs were treated at 250 °C to confirm whether they can withstand the CTF preparation conditions. Similar to the initial CDs, the calcined sample retained its blue fluorescence emission and O-related functional groups (Fig. S12). Furthermore, a pure CTF and CD mixture (CDs/CTFs) was calcined at 250 °C to prepare another sample for comparison. The resultant CDs/CTFs exhibited a photocatalytic activity similar to that of the secondary calcination of CTFs and inferior to that of the untreated CTFs (Fig. 3(e)). These controlled experimental results demonstrate that CDs can serve as nucleation seeds to enable the formation of CDs@CTFs.

The electronic state on the CD surface controls charge separation and transfer; however, the electronic state relies heavily on the surface heteroatom groups, including metal ions, which determine their interactions with the surrounding environment [
                           56
                        ]. The zeta potential of the CDs in solution was negative. The degree of electronegativity increased upon the addition of alkali metal ions such as Na+, K+ and Cs+. Under the same conditions, bivalent and multivalent cations, such as Ca2+, Cu2+, and Ce3+, reduced the electronegativity of the CDs, and some even made their potentials positive (Fig. 4(a)
                        ). Sedimentation was visible at the bottom of the solution (Fig. S14). PL spectra of the CD solution before and after the addition of metal ions were acquired. The addition of Cs+ ions did not change the PL peak of the CDs, whereas bivalent and multivalent cations caused the PL peak to blue shift (Fig. 4(b)). Such phenomena confirm that bivalent and multivalent cations simultaneously interact with two or more CDs, leading to instability of their sol solution and a change in their surface electronic states. Regarding the photocatalytic performance (Fig. 4(c)), the H2O2 yield of the CDs@CTFs containing alkali metal ions increased with the atomic number, whereas that of the CDs@CTFs containing bivalent and multivalent cations decreased significantly, as compared with the pure sample, corresponding to the zeta potential change trend.

The authors concluded that the H+ ions of the carboxyl groups on the CD surface may be replaced by alkali metal ions, which adjusts their surface charge distribution, affecting the charge separation and transfer properties (Fig. 5(a)
                        ). First, the chemical state of Cs in CsCl and the as-prepared CDs@CTFs containing Cs+ ions were determined using XPS to confirm this (Fig. 5(b)). The Cs 3d peaks positively shifted by 0.8 eV, suggesting that Cs bonded with O in CDs@CTFs. Second, the O-related groups of the CDs before and after the addition of Cs+ ions were investigated using FTIR spectroscopy (Fig. 5(c)). The stretching peak at 1721 cm–1 considerably decreased [
                           57
                        ]. Thermogravimetric analyses (TGA) were further performed to determine the effects of the introduction of Cs+ on the surface groups of the CDs after calcination at 250 °C. The notable differentiation observed among the three samples was characterized by a second phase of accelerated weight reduction at 300–380 °C, which resulted from the chemical reaction and removal of O-related functional groups (Fig. 5(d)). Consequently, the introduction of Cs+ ions should preserve more O-related groups in the CDs during the preparation of the CDs@CTFs. This deduction is also supported by the FTIR spectra of the CDs@CTFs containing Cs+ ions (Fig. 5(e)).

Third, the photocatalytic H2O2 activity of the control sample, in which CDs@CTFs were dispersed in a solution of Cs+ ions, was lower than that of the pure CDs@CTFs (Fig. 5(f)). This indicates that CDs@CTFs cannot directly interact with Cs+ ions to improve the photocatalytic H2O2 activity owing to insufficient carboxyl groups. Finally, the CDs were treated with NH3·H2O to obtain NCDs via an amidation reaction [
                           43
                        ]. The original CDs were substituted with NCDs to prepare NCDs@CTFs. The optimal NCD content added to the preparation system was consistent with that of the original CDs; however, pure NCDs@CTFs exhibited a higher H2O2 production rate than CDs@CTFs. This was attributed to the surface functionalization of the amino groups (Fig. S17), which modulate the electric structures on the CD surface [
                           58,59
                        ]. Interestingly, the introduction of Cs+ ions degraded the photosynthetic H2O2 performance of the NCDs@CTFs (Fig. 5(g)). Considering the surface group differences of the CDs, it can be deduced that the interaction of NCDs with Cs+ ions is inhibited because of the replacement of –COOH groups by –CONH2. The control experiments revealed that the carboxylic acid groups on the surface of the CDs could act as active sites for the WOR, which corresponds with the CV results discussed in Section 3.1.

The CTF PL spectra exhibited blue fluorescence and the spectral intensity decreased with the introduction of CDs and Cs+ ions (Fig. 6(b)), suggesting that the recombination of electrons and holes was suppressed [
                           60
                        ]. TFS showed that the photogenerated carriers in CDs@CTFs with and without Cs+ ions were endowed with more time for separation and transfer than those in the pure CTFs (Fig. 6(c)). EIS was used to study the effect of the contact between the CDs and CTFs on charge transfer [
                           61
                        ]. As shown in Fig. 6(d), the interfacial resistance of the CDs@CTFs was significantly lower than that of the CTFs. In particular, the addition of Cs+ ions further decreased the resistance of CDs@CTFs. Therefore, Cs+ ions can strengthen the driving force, for example, the internal electric field that propels carrier migration to the surface. This was also corroborated by the photocurrent responses, in which the photocurrent density order was: CDs@CTFs with Cs+ ions > CDs@CTFs > CTFs (Fig. 6(e)).
